# 5. Trading Idea

## Momentum-Based Moving Average Strategy

A simple momentum trading strategy was proposed using moving average crossovers.

Strategy Logic:

* Buy Signal:

  * Generated when the 20-day moving average rises above the 50-day moving average.

* Sell Signal:

  * Generated when the 20-day moving average falls below the 50-day moving average.

This strategy is based on the assumption that strong upward momentum may continue in the short term.

The strategy attempts to:

* Capture upward market trends
* Reduce exposure during downward momentum
* Improve trading discipline using rule-based decisions

The strategy is simple, interpretable, and widely used in financial markets.



# 6. Backtesting Approach

The proposed strategy can be evaluated using historical market data through backtesting.

Backtesting involves applying the trading rules to historical stock price data to measure how the strategy would have performed in the past.

The following evaluation metrics can be used:

| Metric           | Purpose                            |
| ---------------- | ---------------------------------- |
| Total Return     | Measures profitability             |
| Win Rate         | Percentage of successful trades    |
| Sharpe Ratio     | Measures risk-adjusted return      |
| Maximum Drawdown | Measures largest portfolio decline |
| Volatility       | Measures strategy risk             |


The strategy performance should also be compared against a simple buy-and-hold approach to determine whether the trading rules add value.



# 7. Risks and Limitations

Although the proposed strategy may provide useful insights, several limitations and risks exist.

## 7.1 Historical Bias

Past market behavior may not repeat in future market conditions.

Strategies that perform well historically may fail under changing economic conditions.



## 7.2 False Signals

Moving average strategies may generate incorrect signals during sideways or highly volatile markets.

This can lead to unnecessary trades and reduced profitability.



## 7.3 Market Volatility

Unexpected macroeconomic events, geopolitical risks, and earnings announcements can significantly affect stock prices.

These events may reduce the reliability of technical indicators.



## 7.4 Transaction Costs

Frequent trading may increase:

* Brokerage costs
* Slippage
* Tax implications

These costs may reduce actual strategy profitability.



## 7.5 Overfitting

Strategies optimized too heavily using historical data may become overly specialized and fail in live trading environments.



